			<h2 id="timeline">
				<span class="hash">#</span>Realistic Timelines: What to Expect
			</h2>
			<p>Instamart&rsquo;s official guidance often quotes a fast
				turnaround, but the honest, real-world picture depends heavily on
				how prepared your brand is. Setting the right expectation upfront
				avoids frustration later:</p>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Weeks 1&ndash;2 &mdash; Registration &amp;
						documents.</strong> Supplier empanelment, KYC, and getting every document
					clean and consistent. Gaps here are the single biggest source of
					delay.</li>
				<li><strong>Weeks 2&ndash;4 &mdash; Commercial
						alignment.</strong> Agreeing terms, target cities, and the SKU shortlist
					with the Category Manager.</li>
				<li><strong>Weeks 3&ndash;6 &mdash; NPI &amp;
						catalogue.</strong> Submitting each SKU for approval; this timeline is
					driven almost entirely by how catalogue-ready your products are.</li>
				<li><strong>Weeks 5&ndash;8 &mdash; Inventory &amp;
						go-live.</strong> Dispatching stock against purchase orders and going live
					for minutes-delivery.</li>
			</ul>
			<p>For a well-prepared brand, roughly six to eight weeks is a
				realistic end-to-end timeline. Brands that start without documents
				or a compliant catalogue can stretch to two to four months &mdash;
				almost always because of avoidable rework. IARDO&rsquo;s entire
				approach is built around removing that rework, so you move through
				each stage the first time rather than the third.</p>

			<h2 id="npi">
				<span class="hash">#</span>NPI &amp; Catalogue Setup
				(Instamart-Specific)
			</h2>
			<p>NPI &mdash; New Product Introduction &mdash; is the step that
				trips up most first-time suppliers. Every single SKU is individually
				reviewed and approved by Swiggy&rsquo;s catalogue team before it can
				go live. To pass cleanly, each product needs:</p>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Compliant titles</strong> in Instamart&rsquo;s
					required format (brand, product, variant, pack size)</li>
				<li><strong>High-quality images</strong> meeting minimum
					specifications (multiple images per SKU on a clean background)</li>
				<li><strong>GS1-registered barcodes</strong> and correct HSN
					codes</li>
				<li><strong>MRP on pack</strong> matching the catalogue, with <strong>FSSAI
						details visible</strong> on packaging for food</li>
				<li><strong>Adequate shelf life</strong> remaining at the point
					of inwarding</li>
			</ul>
			<p>IARDO prepares your entire catalogue to NPI standards before
				submission, so approvals move quickly instead of bouncing back for
				corrections.</p>
			<p>NPI approval is not a formality &mdash; it is where many
				launches quietly lose weeks. Each rejection sends a SKU back to the
				start of the queue, so the goal is to get every product right the
				first time. The catalogue team checks not only that fields are
				filled, but that images, titles, and pack information are consistent
				with each other and with the physical product that will actually
				arrive at the dark store.</p>

			<h3>Instamart Catalogue Best Practices</h3>
			<p>A catalogue that clears NPI cleanly and then sells well tends
				to share a few characteristics:</p>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Search-friendly titles</strong> that lead with
					brand and product, then variant and pack size, so customers find
					you the way they actually search.</li>
				<li><strong>Clean, consistent imagery</strong> &mdash; multiple
					angles on a white background, accurate colour, and no misleading
					claims or unapproved offer text baked into images.</li>
				<li><strong>Accurate pack and MRP data</strong> that exactly
					matches what is printed on the product, avoiding the mismatches
					that trigger rejections.</li>
				<li><strong>Correct categorisation</strong> so your SKU sits
					where shoppers expect it and competes in the right set.</li>
				<li><strong>Complete compliance</strong> &mdash; FSSAI details,
					net quantity, manufacturer information, and barcodes all present
					and correct.</li>
			</ul>
			<p>IARDO builds your catalogue to these standards from day one,
				so you clear NPI faster and go live with listings that are already
				set up to convert.</p>

			<h2 id="cost">
				<span class="hash">#</span>Cost of Selling on Swiggy Instamart
			</h2>
			<p>Selling on Instamart involves several cost layers: a
				category-based commission on each sale, inwarding charges per unit,
				daily storage fees, applicable GST on platform fees, and a
				promotional investment to build early visibility. There is no fee to
				register as a supplier &mdash; the costs come once you are live and
				selling.</p>
			<p>
				The exact figures depend on your category, pricing, and the terms
				agreed with your Category Manager, so a real cost picture is best
				built for your specific SKUs. IARDO walks you through the complete,
				current numbers during your onboarding consultation and helps you
				price every SKU with the full cost factored in &mdash; before you go
				live, not after &mdash; so your margins are protected from day one.
				For a general overview, see our guide on <a class="inline"
					href="${pageContext.request.contextPath}/blog/swiggy-instamart-commission-charges">Swiggy
					Instamart commission and charges</a>.
			</p>
			<p>The reason we keep the specifics to a consultation is simple:
				the numbers that matter for your business depend on your exact
				category, pack sizes, and negotiated terms, and a generic figure can
				be misleading either way. What every brand should take from this
				section is the principle &mdash; build the complete cost of selling
				into your pricing before launch, plan a sensible promotional budget
				for the early weeks, and treat margin as something to protect
				deliberately rather than discover by accident.</p>

			<h2 id="first60">
				<span class="hash">#</span>After Go-Live: The First 60 Days
			</h2>
			<p>Going live is the start, not the finish. Instamart&rsquo;s
				ranking is real-time and hyperlocal, so the first two months matter
				enormously for building momentum. Success in this window comes down
				to a few things:</p>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Availability &amp; fill rate</strong> &mdash;
					staying in stock is the strongest ranking signal; stockouts hurt
					visibility fast</li>
				<li><strong>Velocity &amp; conversion</strong> &mdash; products
					that sell get pushed to more customers</li>
				<li><strong>Ratings &amp; reviews</strong> &mdash; early
					positive reviews compound visibility</li>
				<li><strong>Advertising</strong> &mdash; sponsored/item-boost,
					banner, browse-boost, and inline search formats accelerate
					discovery</li>
				<li><strong>Promotional investment</strong> &mdash; a planned
					budget in the first weeks builds the sell-through Swiggy reorders
					against</li>
			</ul>
			<p>IARDO supports you through this window with inventory
				planning, listing optimisation, and advertising guidance &mdash; so
				early traction turns into sustained reorders and city expansion.</p>

			<h2 id="advertising">
				<span class="hash">#</span>Advertising on Swiggy Instamart
			</h2>
			<p>Once you are live, advertising is one of the fastest ways to
				build the visibility and velocity that Instamart&rsquo;s ranking
				rewards. The platform offers several ad formats, each suited to a
				different goal:</p>
			<div class="perks">
				<div class="card">
					<h4>
						<span class="v">&#10003;</span>Sponsored / Item Boost
					</h4>
					<p>Promotes individual SKUs higher in search and category
						listings &mdash; the workhorse format for driving sales on
						specific products.</p>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<h4>
						<span class="v">&#10003;</span>Banner Ads
					</h4>
					<p>Prominent placements on home and category screens to build
						brand awareness and launch-phase visibility.</p>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<h4>
						<span class="v">&#10003;</span>Browse Boost
					</h4>
					<p>Improves your visibility as customers browse relevant
						categories, capturing demand at the discovery stage.</p>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<h4>
						<span class="v">&#10003;</span>Inline Search Banner
					</h4>
					<p>High-visibility placements within search results, connecting
						intent-driven shoppers directly with your products.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<p>Advertising works best when it is paired with strong
				availability and good ratings &mdash; paying to send customers to a
				product that is out of stock or poorly reviewed simply wastes
				budget. IARDO helps you sequence advertising sensibly, so spend only
				goes to work where it will actually compound. One useful caution
				worth building into your reporting: measure returns against the net
				transaction value Swiggy realises, not against MRP, so your ROAS
				figures reflect reality rather than flattering headline numbers.</p>

			<h2 id="mistakes">
				<span class="hash">#</span>Common Instamart Onboarding Mistakes to
				Avoid
			</h2>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Treating it like a marketplace</strong> &mdash;
					misunderstanding the B2B supply model leads to wrong expectations
					on pricing and control.</li>
				<li><strong>Underestimating NPI</strong> &mdash; non-compliant
					titles, images, or barcodes cause repeated catalogue rejections.</li>
				<li><strong>Name and GST mismatches</strong> &mdash; the most
					common reason applications stall.</li>
				<li><strong>Launching too many SKUs</strong> &mdash; a focused
					set of high-demand SKUs outperforms a scattered catalogue.</li>
				<li><strong>Ignoring the first 60 days</strong> &mdash; going
					live without an availability and advertising plan wastes the
					momentum window.</li>
			</ul>

			<h2 id="portal">
				<span class="hash">#</span>Managing Your Instamart Business After
				Launch
			</h2>
			<p>Going live is the beginning of an ongoing operation, not the
				end of a project. Instamart gives suppliers tools and reporting to
				manage inventory, track sales and settlements, monitor listing
				performance, and run advertising. Using these well is what separates
				brands that plateau from brands that keep growing:</p>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Inventory &amp; replenishment</strong> &mdash;
					keeping the right stock in the right dark stores to avoid the
					stockouts that quietly kill ranking.</li>
				<li><strong>Performance monitoring</strong> &mdash; watching
					velocity, conversion, and ratings by SKU and city, and acting on
					what the data shows.</li>
				<li><strong>Settlements &amp; reconciliation</strong> &mdash;
					tracking payments against stock supplied and sold, and catching
					discrepancies early.</li>
				<li><strong>Continuous optimisation</strong> &mdash; refining
					titles, images, pricing inputs, and advertising as you learn what
					your customers respond to.</li>
			</ul>
			<p>IARDO supports you across this ongoing work, so onboarding
				turns into durable, compounding growth rather than a strong start
				that fades.</p>

